

'''Dogliotti's principle''' is a principle in epidural anaesthesia first described by  Professor [[Achille Mario Dogliotti]] in 1933.<ref name=Dogliotti1933>{{cite journal|last=Dogliotti|first=AM|title=Research and clinical observations on spinal anesthesia: with special reference to the peridural technique|journal=[[Anesthesia & Analgesia]]|volume=12|issue=2|pages=59–65|year=1933|pmid=|pmc=|doi=|url=http://www.anesthesia-analgesia.org/content/12/2/59.full.pdf}}</ref> It is a method for the identification of the [[epidural space]], a [[potential space]]. As a needle is advanced through the [[ligamentum flavum]], to the [[epidural space]], with constant pressure applied to the piston of a syringe, loss of resistance occurs once the needle enters the subdural space due to the change in pressure.<ref>{{cite journal  |author=Iklé A|title=Preliminary report of new technique for epidural anaesthesia. |journal=[[British Journal of Anaesthesia]] |volume=22 |issue=3 |pages=150–5
 |month = July |year=1950 |pmid=15426701|doi=10.1093/bja/22.3.150 }}</ref><ref name="wilson">{{cite journal  |author=Wilson MJA|title=Epidural endeavour and the pressure principle. |journal=Anaesthesia |volume=62 |pages=319–324 |year=2007 |url = http://www3.interscience.wiley.com/cgi-bin/fulltext/118530330/PDFSTART |doi=10.1111/j.1365-2044.2007.05063.x |pmid=17381564 |issue=4 }}</ref> The identification of this space, allows subsequent administration of epidural anaesthesia, a technique used primarily for [[analgesia]] during [[childbirth]].

This technique remains in use at {{As of|2007|alt=present}}, and is commonly referred to the loss of resistance to saline technique (LORS) or its variation, the loss of resistance to air technique (LORA). These use, respectively, saline or air to identify the epidural space. The LORS technique is generally favoured due to the increased complication risk with the LORA technique such as [[pneumocephalus]] or [[air embolism]].<ref name="wilson" /><ref>{{cite journal |author=Naulty JS, Ostheimer GW, Datta S, Knapp R, Weiss JB |title=Incidence of venous air embolism during epidural catheter insertion |journal=Anesthesiology |volume=57 |issue=5 |pages=410–2 |year=1982 |month=November |pmid=7137620 |doi=10.1097/00000542-198211000-00010 |url=http://meta.wkhealth.com/pt/pt-core/template-journal/lwwgateway/media/landingpage.htm?issn=0003-3022&volume=57&issue=5&spage=410}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |author=Simopoulos T, Peeters-Asdourian C |title=Pneumocephalus after cervical epidural steroid injection |journal=Anesth. Analg. |volume=92 |issue=6 |pages=1576–7 |year=2001 |month=June |pmid=11375849 |url=http://www.anesthesia-analgesia.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&pmid=11375849}}</ref>

